data.content:
Here's what happened and how to fix it:

## The Problem: C# 14 Span Overload Resolution

In C# 14, new built-in span conversions cause `array.Contains(num)` to bind to **`MemoryExtensions.Contains`** (a `Span`-based method) instead of **`Enumerable.Contains`**. Expression trees cannot represent `Span<T>` methods, so this throws at runtime.

## The Fix

Cast the array to `IEnumerable<T>` to force the LINQ binding:

```csharp
// Option 1: Cast
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => ((IEnumerable<int>)array).Contains(num);

// Option 2: .AsEnumerable()
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => array.AsEnumerable().Contains(num);

// Option 3: Explicit static call
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => Enumerable.Contains(array, num);
```

All three options force the compiler to resolve to `Enumerable.Contains`, which is representable in expression trees. This same issue can affect `.Reverse()` on arrays (now resolves to the in-place `Span` version).
